<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8"?>

<section xml:id="sec-permutations-i" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Permutations I</title>
    <objectives component="outcomes">
        <introduction>
            <p>
            <dl>
                <li>
                    <title>Strand</title>
                    <p>3.0 Statistics and Probability</p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Sub-Strand</title>
                    <p>3.1 Permutations and Combinations</p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Specific Learning Outcomes</title> 
                    <p>Perform permutations involving real life situations</p>
                </li>
                <li component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Grade Level</title>
                    <p>11</p>
                </li>
                <li component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Estimated Duration</title>
                    <p>40 minutes</p>
                </li>
            </dl>
            </p>
        </introduction>
    </objectives>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Problem-Solving and Discovery</title>
        <dl>
            <li>
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p>10 minutes</p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Objective</title>
                <p>To understand that order matters when assigning specific roles or positions.</p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Teacher's Role</title>
                <p>Lead the "Class Elections" task. Ask students if the outcome is different if Person A is Captain vs. Person B being Captain. This highlights the concept of ordered arrangements.</p>
            </li>
        </dl>
    </axiom>

    <activity>
        <title>The Leadership Committee</title>
        <statement>
            <p>
                In a class of 10 students, you need to elect a <strong>prefect </strong> and a <strong>assistant prefect</strong>. 
                <ol>
                    <li>How many different students could be chosen as Prefect?</li>
                    <li>Once a Prefect is chosen, how many students are left to choose from for Assistant Prefect?</li>
                    <li>Multiply these choices together. How many total ways can this leadership pair be formed?</li>
                    <li>If we were just picking two "helpers" with no titles, would the answer be the same? Why or why not?</li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </statement>
    </activity>

    <insight>
        <title>Permutations: When Order Matters</title>
        <p>
            A <term>permutation</term> is an arrangement of items where the <strong>order</strong> is important. For example, in a queue or a race, finishing 1st is different from finishing 2nd.
        </p>
        <p>
            <p><strong>1. The Permutation Formula:</strong></p>
            <line>When we want to choose <m>r</m> items from a total of <m>n</m> items and arrange them in order, we use the formula:</line>
            <me>_nP_r = P(n, r) = \frac{n!}{(n-r)!}</me>
        </p>
        <p>
           <p> <strong>2. Applying the Formula</strong></p>
            <line>If you are picking a Prefect and Assistant Prefect from 5 people, you are looking for <m>_5P_2</m>:</line>
            <me>_5P_2 = \frac{5!}{(5-2)!} = \frac{5!}{3!} = \frac{5 \times 4 \times 3!}{3!} = 20 \text{ ways.}</me>
        </p>
        <p>
           <p> <strong>3. Simplifying Expressions:</strong></p>
            <line>Permutation problems often involve dividing and subtracting factorials. Always perform the subtraction in the denominator first before expanding the numerator.</line>
        </p>
    </insight>

    <xi:include href="../lesson-plan-templates/example-intro.ptx" />

    <example>
       
        <statement>
            <p>1. There are 6 people waiting in a line at a bank. In how many different orders can they be served?</p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                Since all 6 people are being arranged, we are looking for <m>_6P_6</m> (which is simply <m>6!</m>):
                <me>_6P_6 = \frac{6!}{(6-6)!} = \frac{6!}{0!} = \frac{720}{1} = 720 \text{ ways.}</me>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <example>
    
        <statement>
            <p>2. In a race with 12 runners, how many ways can the Gold, Silver, and Bronze medals be awarded?</p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                We are choosing and arranging 3 runners out of 12:
                <me>_{12}P_3 = \frac{12!}{(12-3)!} = \frac{12!}{9!}</me>
                <me>12 \times 11 \times 10 = 1,320 \text{ ways.}</me>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <example>
        
        <statement>
            <p>3. Evaluate <m>_8P_4</m>.</p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                <me>_8P_4 = \frac{8!}{(8-4)!} = \frac{8!}{4!}</me>
                <me>8 \times 7 \times 6 \times 5 = 1,680</me>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <example>
        
        <statement>
            <p>4. Show that <m>_nP_1 = n</m>.</p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                Using the formula:
                <me>_nP_1 = \frac{n!}{(n-1)!} = \frac{n \times (n-1)!}{(n-1)!} = n</me>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <example>
      
        <statement>
            <p>5. How many 3-letter "words" (even if they don't make sense) can be formed from the letters in the word <strong>MATHS</strong>?</p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                The word "MATHS" has 5 unique letters. We want to arrange 3 of them:
                <me>_5P_3 = \frac{5!}{(5-3)!} = \frac{5 \times 4 \times 3 \times 2!}{2!} = 60 \text{ words.}</me>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <xi:include href="../lesson-plan-templates/assessment-intro.ptx" />

    <exercises>
        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>Calculate <m>_7P_2</m>.</p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p><m>\frac{7!}{5!} = 7 \times 6 = 42</m></p>
            </solution>
        </exercise>

        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>A Mathematics club at Marakusi Comprehensive School has 15 members. In how many ways can they elect a President, Secretary, and Treasurer?</p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p><m>_{15}P_3 = 15 \times 14 \times 13 = 2,730</m> ways.</p>
            </solution>
        </exercise>

        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>There are 5 empty seats on a bus and 3 people board. In how many different ways can they be seated?</p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p><m>_5P_3 = \frac{5!}{2!} = 5 \times 4 \times 3 = 60</m> ways.</p>
            </solution>
        </exercise>

        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>Evaluate <me>\frac{_6P_3}{3!}</me></p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    <m>_6P_3 = 6 \times 5 \times 4 = 120</m>.
                    <m>120 / 6 = 20</m>.
                </p>
            </solution>
        </exercise>

        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>If <m>_nP_2 = 56</m>, find <m>n</m>.</p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    <m>n(n-1) = 56</m>. 
                    We look for two consecutive numbers that multiply to 56. 
                    <m>8 \times 7 = 56</m>, so <m>n = 8</m>.
                </p>
            </solution>
        </exercise>
    </exercises>

</section>